<HEADLINE> U.S. Wants to Host Another World Cup by 2010 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Soccer Federation
(USSF) hopes to host another World Cup in 2010 or 2014, said the
head of the USSF at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Alan Rothenberg said:"We would love to host another World Cup.
It's something we will absolutely look at. But I think it can't be
before 2010 and probably more likely in 2014. As soon as the
bidding opens up, I'm sure FIFA will put us at the head of the
line."
</P>
<P>
The 1994 World Cup, staged in the United States for the first
time, was regarded as a success from a public and commercial
standpoint. The 52-game tournament attracted 3.5 million
spectators at nine venues and reached good television ratings in
this country.
</P>
<P>
FIFA officials were satisfied with the results and indicated
they would like to see another U.S. bid in the future.
</P>
<P>
The 2002 World Cup is scheduled to be shared by Japan and South
Korea. Germany and England are bidding for the 2006 tournament,
and FIFA has showed its attitute to back up South Africa for the
2010 version. That likely would open 2014 for a North American or
South American country.
</P>
<P>
Rothenberg said there haven't been any formal discussions with
FIFA officials about the bidding attempt.
</P>
<P>
The United States will host the Women's World Cup next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
