<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-8 Ministers to Meet on Indian-Pakistan Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Britain announced Saturday foreign
ministers from the Group of Eight (G-8) countries would meet in
London next month to discuss a joint approach towards the series
of nuclear tests carried out by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a statement issued
Saturday that the London meeting of G-8, which consists of the
United States, Canada, Germany, France, Italy, Japan, Britain and
Russia, would be held on June 12.
</P>
<P>
Cook, whose country is the current G-8 president, stressed that
the G-8 ministers were expected to "coordinate our approach to
Pakistan and India in the light of the nuclear tests."
</P>
<P>
The ministers would consider "in particular how we can most
effectively bring both of them within the global non-proliferation
regime and encourage them to address the roots of the tension
between them," Cook said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Early Saturday, Cook unleashed verbal attacks upon Pakistan for
undertaking another round of nuclear tests saying this latest
action was "flagrant disregard" of international opinion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
