<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of Sans Papiers Immigrants Receive Legal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 50 percent of some 145,000
registered immigrants without residency papers, called sans
papiers here, have received legal residency in France since the
Socialist government began to re-examine their cases 11 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry said that 85 percent of the applications
for legal residency from the 145,000 sans papiers have been
studied and given answers, with nearly 50 percent of them being
positive.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for applying for legal residency by hundreds of
thousands of sans papiers, most of them Africans and Arabs but
also Asians, is due on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Most of those whose applications were rejected are unmarried
young people, as the French government gives prior considerations
to those who have family members living in France.
</P>
<P>
The French government estimates that 150,000 more unregistered
sans papiers are living and working illegally in France.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement congratulated the
governments of different prefects on almost completing the job
without causing much trouble from the political rightwing rivals
of the leftwing government.
</P>
<P>
But the government is criticized by some for doing it in an
arbitrary rather than humanitarian way when issuing residency
rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
