<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Crackdown on Tax Dodgers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Russia's newly-appointed director of
the state tax service, Boris Fyodorov, has decided to tighten tax
collection in a bid to raise revenue owed to the state.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Kommersant Daily on Saturday, Fyodorov
said production and service industries, including the fields of
raw materials, oil and liquor, should bring in more tax revenue
than they do.
</P>
<P>
Measures would be imposed equally on anyone, Fyodorov said in
response to the question whether monopolies having debts to the
budget would be included in the penalty.
</P>
<P>
"If an enterprise does not pay taxes, it should be declared
bankrupt. Everyone should be treated on an equal footing." he said.
</P>
<P>
Tax collection was especially poor with regard to individuals,
Fyodorov said, adding only four million out of the 150 million
population filled out income tax declarations for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Tax dodging, particularly by some conglomerates, had deprived
the state of revenue, compounding the country's economic woes and
problems caused by devaluation of the currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
