<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Nuclear Testing, Expression of Self-Defense: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's decision to exercise
the nuclear option is "an expression of self-defense," Foreign
Secretary Shamshad Ahmed told a press conference Saturday
afternoon after the detonation of another nuclear device earlier
in the day.
</P>
<P>
"In restoring the strategic balance in the South Asian region,
Pakistan has given only a bare minimum response," the foreign
secretary said at the press conference which was attended by about
150 journalists.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan conducted five nuclear tests on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan completed the current series by another nuclear test
Saturday, said Shamshad.
</P>
<P>
"All the tests conducted were fully contained. There was no
release of radio-activity. The results were as expected," Shamshad
said, adding that "the devices tested correspond to weapons
configuration, compatible with delivery systems."
</P>
<P>
He said that "it is not our intention to enter into an arms
race. The history of the Cold War era shows that such disastrous
races are counter-productive and definitely not sustainable."
</P>
<P>
"The only race we propose to run is for economic development,"
said Shamshad, adding that more than one billion people of South
Asia do not want and certainly cannot afford to divert their
precious resources for a nuclear confrontation in the region.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Pakistan has always exercised maximum restraint.
It will continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
"Our capabilities demonstrated by our six nuclear tests are
only for self-defense and only to deter aggression," stressed the
foreign secretary.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad said India initiated its nuclear program right after
its independence and detonated a device in, as early as, 1974.
</P>
<P>
"New Delhi then feverishly engaged in a massive nuclear and
missile program to satisfy its grandiose ambitions and
hegemonistic designs," the foreign secretary said.
</P>
<P>
"The fact of our existence as the neighbor of an expansionist
and a hegemonistic power taught us the inevitable lesson that we
must search for security," he said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the real causes of insecurity, conflicts and
tensions in the South Asian region need to be redressed. "It is,
therefore, imperative to find a peaceful and just solution of the
Jammu and Kashmir dispute," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the genuine contribution to peace and security
can be made by constructive engagement in the search for permanent
solutions.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad said that Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has affirmed
Pakistan's determination to engage in "a constructive dialogue"
with other countries especially major powers to determine new ways
and means to promote the goal of nuclear disarmament and
non-proliferation in the world.
</P>
<P>
Sharif has also reaffirmed the determination of his government
to resume Pak-India dialogue to address all outstanding issues
including the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir as well as peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to enter into discussions with India for
taking all steps that are necessary to ensure mutual restraint and
equitable measures for nuclear stabilization in the South Asian
region," Shamshad said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary said that "compelling security concerns
have to be discussed together with measures to promote the goals
of non-proliferation. Global non-proliferation regimes can best be
promoted by addressing the very factors that impel proliferation."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, as a responsible nation, assures the international
community and in particular India of its willingness "to enter
into immediate discussions to address all matters of peace and
security including urgent measures to prevent the dangers of
nuclear conflagration," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
