<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Rules out Destructive Quakes in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The two minor earthquakes that hit
Beijing this evening do not prelude major ones in the Chinese
capital, according to an official with the State Seismological
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think Beijing will be hit by destructive earthquakes
measuring more than five on the Ritcher Scale in the
near future," said Ding Jianhai, head of the Center for Earthquake
Analysis and Prediction.
</P>
<P>
At 7:37 and 7:42 this evening (local time) this evening,
Beijing was hit by two minor quakes measuring 3.1 on the Ritcher
Scale. The quakes' epicenters were located at around Fengtai
District, 15 kilometers away from the center of Beijing, or 39.53
degrees north latitude and 116.18 degrees east longitude. They
were strongly felt in Fengtai, Shijingshan, Haidian and some other
areas of the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
"As the quakes are the ones that occurred nearest to the city
center this year, so they have drawn close attention of local
residents," Ding said.
</P>
<P>
No damage of houses has been reported, according to Ding.
</P>
</TEXT>
