<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturing Industries Slow Down in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 31 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's industrial foundation
is headed toward collapse as manufacturing operation rates in some
industries plunged to as low as 40 percent, the Federation of
Korean Industries (KFI) said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a report, the FKI said that the production of major
manufacturing industries have nosedived by 20 to 30 percent since
the nation signed an agreement with the International Monetary
Fund for a rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars last December,
after suffering a serious financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Operational reduction is particularly serious in auto,
machinery, electric and steel industries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The average operating rate of auto assembly plants, for
instance, has dropped from 65 percent last November to the current
42 percent, mainly because of sluggish domestic sales,
bankruptcies of spare parts suppliers and the tight liquidity
situation.
</P>
<P>
The operating rates of electric appliances, machinery and steel
industries tumbled to 60.3 percent, 69.8 percent, and 75.5 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Setbacks in factory operations are feared to weigh down the
industrial base, wiping out the potential for future economic
growth, said the federation.
</P>
<P>
The FKI proposed that the government cut interest rates, expand
trade financing, lower import duties and tax rates and advance its
budget spending to stave off a further worsening economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
