<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Surmounting Drugs Problem, Arduous Task </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is facing a serious and
complex situation in drug abuse. Despite consistent efforts, the
government has yet to surmount the crucial problem which has
rendered millions of people hooked on narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Until the late 1970s, many of the Pakistani people even did not
know what heroin was. However, since then, the drug abuse
situation in this South Asian nation has been increasingly serious
mainly because of the long-running war in neighboring Afghanistan
and poppy production in tribal areas.
</P>
<P>
Official data suggest that in the early 1980's only a very
small number of people, who already addicted to hashish, took
heroin just for entertainment. The drug abuse has now become a
problem of national importance.
</P>
<P>
Media reports suggest that more than half of the total drug
production worldwide is smuggled from Pakistan and Afghanistan to
Europe, Middle East and northern America, while the rest comes
from the well-known "Golden Triangle".
</P>
<P>
Official studies show that heroin is being processed from opium
by the local tribesmen living in Pakistan's Federal Administered
Tribal Areas (FATA).
</P>
<P>
"Opium extracted from poppy is processed and converted into
heroin powder at make-shift laboratories and then marketed ," said
an official attached to the Pakistan Narcotics Control Board
(PNCB).
</P>
<P>
Sources from PNCB's regional office in Peshawar, capital of
North West Frontier Province (NWFP), said that cultivation of
poppy got boosted in tribal areas as well in some districts of
NWFP throughout the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
There had been a record bumper poppy crop in the mid 1980s with
a cultivated area of 80,000 acres in Gadoon Amazai, Malakand,
Buner, Dir, Kaladhaka and Mohmond and Bajaur agencies in tribal
areas.
</P>
<P>
However, the Pakistani government, under the pressure both from
home and abroad, has actively intervened for the last several
years and enforced a ban on cultivation of poppy which has
resulted in a significant decrease.
</P>
<P>
And these measures are supplemented by checking smuggling of
heroin and rehabilitation of drug addicts all over the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign countries as well as the United Nations
Drugs Control Program have been providing financial assistance for
Pakistan's poppy growing areas in the settled districts of NWFP
and FATA to enable farmers to look for substitute means of
income.
</P>
<P>
And various international aid programs have helped the
Pakistani government create more job opportunities for the local
residents and provide funding to development schemes ranging from
agriculture sector to communication.
</P>
<P>
With the strict enforcement of the ban on poppy cultivation,
people of Gadoon Amazai and adjoining areas have abandoned
cultivation of poppy crop.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no poppy crop in Gadoon Amazai area since the
inception of the development projects," said Ghafoor Jadoon, local
representative elected to the Provincial Assembly of the NWFP.
</P>
<P>
The government has also beefed up its measures to check
smuggling of contraband drugs including heroin and hashish.
</P>
<P>
It has set up an Anti-Narcotics Force (ANF) comprising
personnel from the Pakistani Army in addition to the police and
customs squads.
</P>
<P>
ANF has been assigned dual responsibility including combating
smuggling and detecting assets accumulated from drug money. It is
actively trying to detect the assets of smugglers in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In addition to these steps, dozens of smugglers have been
arrested and tons of drugs have been seized by the ANF regional
office in Peshawar this year.
</P>
<P>
The Peshawar office of ANF, headed by Brigadier Behramand Shah,
seized 2050 kilograms of hashish and 43 kilograms of heroin
carried on two vehicles late last month and arrested the
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the worst victims of the drugs business are
the Pakistani youths aged between 20 to 35. The existing treatment
and rehabilitation centers do not match the increasing number of
addicts in the country.
</P>
<P>
Only a few government hospitals with limited capacity offer
treatment facilities to the drug-ridden youths.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the number of drug addicts in Pakistan is
likely to grow and the drug abuse situation will remain serious
until poppy cultivation is banned and production of heroin and
hashish stopped in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
