<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Considering of Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan, who will fight
against the Indiana Pacers with all his talent and courage in Game
7 of the Eastern Conference finals late today at United Centre,
said his retirement is a certain thing.
</P>
<P>
"That is certainly a thought," said the 35-year-old. "But
before that, we're going to win Game 7. I haven't played in a Game
7 in six years. You've got to start focusing on that and let that
slide off your back. You've got to laugh and let it go."
</P>
<P>
If the Bulls lose the showdown, the battle might be the final
game for the NBA greatest hero.
</P>
<P>
It's perhaps the ultimate testament to the greatness of Jordan
and the Bulls that they almost never find themselves on the brink
of elimination, deadlocked with everything riding on one game.
</P>
<P>
To presume the Bulls will win Sunday game means ignoring that
Indiana has won three out of the last four games in this series.
It would ignore Jordan tripping over Derrick McKey's foot in the
dying seconds Friday night, or missing two jumpers in the final
minute.
</P>
<P>
But the Pacers should get nervous when they fight at United
Center, where they have lost three straight games in the series.
</P>
<P>
"We're trying to get to the next round," said Jordan. "We don't
have time to think about dynasties and everything else. I'm
looking forward to the challenge. If you had your choice, you'd
rather have it another way. In situations where our backs have
been against the wall, I think we've showed that we can conquer
the situation."
</P>
<P>
But the Bulls reserve guard Jud Buechler voiced out everyone's
inner fear. "I'm sure it has entered everyone's mind that this
could be Michael's last game, Scottie's last in a Bull's uniform."
</P>
<P>
The showdown is more important for Jordan than for anyone
else. It is a stage set only for him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
