<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number Of Handicapped Poor Chinese Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The number of poverty-stricken
handicapped population in China has declined in the last two
decades, thanks to great efforts of the government to assist
the poor.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1997, the figure stood at 13.72 million, 22.87
percent of the country's total handicapped people and 27.4 percent
of all people below the poverty line. There were 17 million
disabled poor people in China at the end of 1976.
</P>
<P>
The figures were provided by the China Federation of
Handicapped People. A latest survey on the issue was conducted by
local federations of the disabled between last November and March
this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the investigation, at the end of last year, China
had 10.59 million poor families with handicapped members. Of them,
7.78 million are able to have enough food and clothing by
joining in government-funded development projects or finding a job
on their own.
</P>
<P>
Some 2.8 million of these families, whose members are unable to
feed themselves, have to live on government relief programs.
</P>
<P>
Of the present 13.72 million poor handicapped people, 87.9
percent live in rural areas and 91.3 percent in underdeveloped
central and western regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
