<HEADLINE> Corretja Wins Rain-delayed Marathon Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Alex Corretja won the blessing of the
rain by ralling from two sets down to beat his Argentine opponent
in the third round match of the French Open tennis tournament here
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Corretja trailed two sets when rain interrupted his match
against Hernan Gumy of Argentina on Saturday, but returned back to
score his marathon win 6-1, 5-7, 6-7 (4/7), 7-5, 9-7 in five hours
and 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
His match became the longest-ever at the championships,
surpassing the previous record of 4 hours and 42 minutes in 1982
when Sweden's Mats Wilander beat Guillermo Vilas of Argentina in
four sets.
</P>
<P>
Corretja, 24 and the 14th seed, now plays Jason Stoltenberg of
Australia for a place in the quarter-finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
