<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Orders Clear Indication of Cigarette Tar Content </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The administrative body of China's
tobacco industry will soon order domestic manufacturers to
indicate cigarette tar contents with accurate figures.
</P>
<P>
The industry also planned to reduce the average content of tar
to less than 15 milligram per cigarette by the year 2000, compared
with some 18 mg at present.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Tobacco Monoply Bureau (STMB)
confirmed the news today, the World No-Tobacco Day when
anti-smoking campaigners raised their voices to warn people,
whether smoking or not, of harms related with smoking cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
"We've decided to implement the order as of July 1, 1998. The
figure of tar contents must be as accurate as to one place of
decimals," Yu Minfang told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
She said consumers were often confused by inaccurate
indications of tar contents on some cigarette cases, which only
read "high", "medium" or "low".
</P>
<P>
Tar in tobacco has long been blamed as a major material to
damage human health, such as leading to cancers.
</P>
<P>
The average tar content has been reduced below 12 mg per
cigarette in many industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
There are only a small number of low-tar cigarettes among some
2,000 brands of Chinese tobacco products. The "medium-tar"
cigarettes, containing about 18 gm of tar each, are popular in
China.
</P>
<P>
But in fact, China's tobacco manufacturers have increased
development and production of low-tar cigarettes under the
pressure from the anti-smoking campaign and increasing fierce
competition from foreign tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
The STMB's decision received a positive response from the China
Association on Tobacco or Health, the leader of the country's
anti-smoking campaign.
</P>
<P>
"China has 320 million smokers, and it's not realistic to ask
them to quit smoking overnight," said Prof. Zhang Yifang, vice
president of the association.
</P>
<P>
"To a certain extent, reducing tar contents may help reduce
health risks caused by smoking," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
