<HEADLINE> Blatter Promises Asia Extra Spots for 2002 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Five places at least will be
alloted to Asia at the 2002 World Cup finals, FIFA presidential
candidate Blatter said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA general secretary insisted that it has already been
agreed that Asia will get extra places in the first World Cup
finals in Asia though he was on the final stretch of an arduous
presidential campaign prior to the vote next week.
</P>
<P>
Japan and South Korea, who will co-host the 2002 World Cup
finals, will get automatic places. But Asia will also get at
least three other guaranteed places, as it did for the World Cup
in France and a playoff chance for another country.
</P>
<P>
Blatter added that it was possible Asia could get a fourth
guaranteed spot in 2002 "and possibly more" if Iran, Japan, Saudi
Arabia and South Korea displayed good performances at this year's
finals.
</P>
<P>
Blatter also implied that Europe was likely to have to give up
one of its spots in four years time. But it was also clear that
the battle is not yet over.
</P>
<P>
Blatter is just over a week away from the FIFA presidential
vote in Paris on June 8 when he will be up against UEFA leader
Lennart Johansson in the vote to succeed Joao Havelange.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss official was in Beijing on Saturday lobbying the
Chinese Football Association's vote. He was to return to Zurich on
Sunday before flying off again to West Africa for a final round of
campaigning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
