<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mutiny Ends in Niger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Niger's Republican guardsmen have
ended a mutiny over back pay and set free a senior officer they
took hostage, a report from Niger's capital Niamey said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
President Ibrahim Bare Mainassara's personal chief of staff
Colonel Hamadou Moussa Gros was quoted as telling state radio
late Saturday that the grumbling guardsmen had agreed with an
order from Mainassara to end the revolt.
</P>
<P>
Regular forces in armored cars remained visible around the
central camp in Niamey, capital of the western African state
where the mutiny erupted, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
"The orders given by the president of the republic have just
been carried out to the letter," Gros said, adding that
Mainassara had congratulated the guardsmen for recognizing that
discipline was paramount for anyone in uniform.
</P>
<P>
Regular forces in the French-speaking country had encircled
the camp and given the guardsmen an ultimatum to free their
hostage or face the use of force. there were no reports of
injuries.
</P>
<P>
A number of mutinies rocked barracks elsewhere in Niger in
February over unpaid wages. Niamey settled those protests with
partial payments.
</P>
<P>
The Republican Guard ensures the security of state
institutions in the former French colony which has an area of
1,267,000 square kilometers with a population of more than eight
million.
</P>
<P>
The government, weighed down by debt and struggling to make
ends meet, owes its 40,000 civil servants around six months'
salary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
