<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12 Police Hurt As Riot Erupts In N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) - Northern Ireland was hit by some of
its worst street violence in more than two years Saturday night as
a 400-strong crowd went on the rampage, according to news from
Portadown, Co Armagh, early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Twelve police officers and three civilians were hurt in a hail
of stones, bottles and petrol bombs in the flashpoint area of
Portadown.
</P>
<P>
The rioting began after nationalists objected to a parade by
the junior orange Order. Petrol and paint bombs, and stones and
bottles were thrown at police, and troops moved in to separate the
rivals.
</P>
<P>
The Royal Ulster Constabulary fired plastic bullets to beat
back the rioting mob coming from the mainly Nationalist housing
estate which was objecting to an attempt by some Loyalists to move
down the road.
</P>
<P>
Police said the junior Orange march involving children up to
the age of 15 had passed off peacefully and was breaking up when
the violence erupted.
</P>
<P>
An RUC spokesman said,"It is the most serious rioting we have
had for a very long time and it is difficult to establish what
sparked it off."
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believe that the violence is a blow to
those who heralded last week's referendum in favor of a new
assembly for Northern Ireland as a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Pressure on the Sinn Fein and the Republican movement has been
stepped up recently when unionists renewed their demands for the
decommissioning of weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
