<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Minister Defends Sinn Fein Party Invitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam
on Sunday defended her decision to invite Sinn Fein leaders to a
Northern Ireland garden party at which Prince Charles will be
guest of honor.
</P>
<P>
Inviting them had been part of the peace process in Northern
Ireland because Sinn Fein had signed up to the peace agreement,
Mowlam told BBC TV.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leaders Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness have not
said if they will attend the garden party, but Mowlam ensured
personally that if Adams and McGuinness do come to the party, they
would not come face-to-face with Prince Charles.
</P>
<P>
"There is doubt whether they will. They are Republicans, they
are not supporters of the monarchy. But if they come, it will be I
that will escort the royal round and I will make very sure who he
meets," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I would not have put them at the garden party in a position
where they would meet Sinn Fein. I have met too many families of
victims -- and the Royal Family in that sense with the death of
Mountbatten are a family that has suffered -- and I wouldn't put
them in that position."
</P>
<P>
Lord Mountbatten, the great uncle of Prince Charles, was killed
with three others, including his 14-year-old grandson, when his
boat was blown up while he was holidaying in the Irish Republic in
1979.
</P>
<P>
The garden party at Hillsborough Castle is one of the major
social events of the year in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The decision to invite the meeting between Adams and Charles,
however, sparked outrage from opposition politicians in Britain
and from Protestant Unionists who said Mowlam was being
insensitive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
