<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Injured as Violence Mars Jewish Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Eleven people were injured in
clashes between ultra-Orthodox Jews and Palestinians Sunday in
East Jerusalem as violence marred the Jewish holiday of Shavuot.
</P>
<P>
The clashes broke out as Orthodox Jews passed by the Muslim
Quarter of the Old City after ending their morning prayer at the
Western Wall to celebrate Shavuot, the Jewish festival commemorating
the obtaining of Torah (Five Law Books of Moses) on Mount Sinai
and marking the start of the harvest season.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted witnesses as saying that Palestinian
residents began the fight by throwing stones at the prayers
and the incident quickly developed into a massive scuffling and
stone throwing. Israeli policemen were also attacked when they
intervened to break up the melee.
</P>
<P>
Four Jews, four Palestinians and three Israeli policemen
were lightly injured and three Palestinian cars damaged in the
clashes, the radio said. Four Palestinian youths were detained
for questioning.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the morning, dozens of Israeli police were
deployed at the Western Wall to prevent confrontation between
Orthodox and Conservative Jews as happened last year on Shavuot,
one of three Jewish pilgrimage festivals beginning on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
