<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Airports Return to Normal After Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Flights from British airports are
slowly returning to normal on Sunday after thousands of travelers
faced delays because of a strike by Spanish air traffic
controllers.
</P>
<P>
At Gatwick airport in London, there was an average delay of up
to three hours on flights to Spain or to destinations such as the
United States or Portugal with routes through Spanish airspace.
</P>
<P>
Worst-hit was thought to be Glasgow city airport in Scotland,
where 1,000 passengers were stranded waiting to board holiday
flights as the Spanish ended their strike, but then began a
work-to-rule.
</P>
<P>
Passengers were asked to check in as normal, but were warned
they could be delayed between two and nine hours.
</P>
<P>
At Manchester Airport, more than 2,000 people were forced to
spend weekend night camped down. One flight was held up by 14
hours.
</P>
<P>
The strike has also affected homeward-bound British holiday
makers, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
