<HEADLINE> Arafat Concludes Visit to UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat left here Sunday morning after reaching an agreement with
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) leaders on holding an expanded Arab
summit in view of the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day stay here, Arafat held talks with UAE
President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan on the latest
developments in the Arab arena and the prospects of convening an
Arab summit.
</P>
<P>
According to well-informed sources here, the Palestinians
accept the convocation of a mini Arab summit as a preliminary step
for an expanded one, provided that all Arab parties concerned with
the peace process take part in the mini summit.
</P>
<P>
These parties are Syria, Lebanon, the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA), Jordan, Egypt as well as certain countries in the
Arab Gulf and the Arab Maghreb Union.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Maghreb Union groups Algeria, Libya, Mauritania,
Morocco and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, an Arab diplomatic source in Riyadh has
ruled out the prospects of convening of a tripartite summit of
Saudi Arabia, Egypt and Syria before an expanded Arab summit.
</P>
<P>
He said that convening a mini Arab summit without the
participation of the PNA would be tantamount to departing the
summit from its prime objective and real meaning.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, well-informed Palestinian sources said that Arafat
will proceed Wednesday to Muscat to discuss with Omani Sultan
Qaboos Bin Said the convening of an Arab summit, and will also
visit Qatar for the same purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
