<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 08:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Stance on Missiles Remains Firm: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides has reiterated that his government's decision to deploy
Russian anti-aircraft missiles remains firm unless the reasons
for which they were ordered are eliminated.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters Saturday night upon his return from his
visits to Dublin and Athens, Kasoulides said "if the reasons which
have forced us to feel the need to order the missiles persist to
exist, then we have no other choice but to bring in the missiles."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered the Russian-made surface-to-air
S-300 missile system in January 1997, which is expected to be
deployed here later this year.
</P>
<P>
The deal has met strong opposition from Turkey, which has
threatened to destroy the missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides argued that the people of Cyprus are facing security
dangers from the Turkish air force.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third in the aftermath of afailed pro-Athens c
oup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained around 40,000 troops in northern Cyprus,
which was declared unilaterally in 1983 by Turkish Cypriots as
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
"Had we been engaged in productive talks which would have
paved the way to peace or had we clinched an agreement on the
demilitarization of Cyprus, then we would reconsider our decision
to deploy the missiles," the foreign minister reiterated.
</P>
<P>
He said President Glafcos Clerides proposed, during last
summer's U.N.-led talks, to the Turkish Cypriot leader "to enter
a dialog with a view to reduce forces and armaments and prohibit
the import of new weapons as part of a plan for the
demilitarization of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Clerides put forward to the U.N. Secretary-General in December
1993 a proposal for the demilitarization of Cyprus, providing for
the disbanding of the Greek Cypriot National Guard and the Turkish
Cypriot armed forces and the simultaneous withdrawal of the
Turkish forces in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his talks in Athens, Kasoulides said his
discussion with his Greek counterpart, Theodoros Pangalos focused
on a review of developments in Cyprus, especially after a visit
here of U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke early this month.
</P>
<P>
"I am very pleased with the understanding that exists between
the Cypriot and the Greek governments," Kasoulides added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 08:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Enters Second Round of Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon started Sunday morning the
second round of its first municipal and mayoral elections in 35
years.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese interior ministry stationed armored personnel carriers
mounted with machine guns at key intersections and deployed troops
outside the polling stations for fear of the violence and unrest
which the country had suffered during the 15-year-old sectarian
civil war.
</P>
<P>
The voting started at 7:00 a.m. local time (4:00 a.m. GMT) and
will close at 5:00 p.m. (1400 GMT) in the North Lebanon
governorate where politicians said there will be no competition as
sharp as in the first round of elections in Mount Lebanon, the
country's central province.
</P>
<P>
In the first round of elections, right-wing Christian groups,
which oppose the Syrian presence and its 40,000 troops in
Lebanon, swept to victory in some parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for Lebanese Christians, nearly counting
for the country's half population, to take part in the elections
after the civil war. They boycotted parliamentary elections in
1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, won in its
stronghold in Beirut's southern suburbs, defeating an alliance
formed by its rival Shiite Muslim Amal Movement led by Parliament
Speaker Nabih Berri and candidates backed Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri.
</P>
<P>
As no security problem took place in the first round of
elections, in which turnout reached as much as 80 percent,
Lebanon's top leaders had expressed confidence in the following
polls in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
But diplomats here said it is still early to forecast the
success of the whole elections as the fiercest race has not come
in the capital of Beirut where has nearly half of the country's
population.
</P>
<P>
A total of 7,662 members for 646 municipals councils, and 2,041
mayors and chiefs in 1,282 towns and villages will be finally
elected in the polls, which started on May 24 and will continue on
the following two Sundays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
