<HEADLINE> Massive Artificial Rainfall in Yellow River Valley Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China recently successfully launched
the second massive artificial rainfall on the upper reaches of the
Yellow River in an effort to save it from drying up.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the water flow dramatically reduced on the upper
reaches of the Yellow River in Qinghai province, posing a threat
to local economic construction.
</P>
<P>
Between the end of April and September of 1997, Qinghai,
located at the source of the Yellow River, invested one million
yuan (120,480 US dollars) in launching the first artificial
rainfall on the upper reaches, bringing 180 million to 280 million
cubic meters of water to the river.
</P>
<P>
The operation was done in an area about 4,000 meters above sea
level where marshland is abundant.
</P>
<P>
The second operation involved a total investment of eight
million yuan from both the central and regional governments. It is
learned artificial rain will be made on the river every year in
the coming three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0078 </DOCNO>
