<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Explores Trade Prospects in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian businessmen
are exploring trade opportunities in their neighboring country,
the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
A Tanzanian trade delegation will travel to Congo (K) during
June 8-15 to explore trade prospects there, said Mbarouk
Mwandoro, director general of the Board of External Trade (BET).
</P>
<P>
The delegation will visit Lubumbashi, a major business center
in southwest Congo (K), where a mini-exhibition will be staged
for four days.
</P>
<P>
Visits to other towns, including Mbujimayi, Kalemie, and
Bukavu will also be arranged by the BET in collaboration with the
Katanga Chamber of Commerce, Mbarouk said, according to a local
press report. But the report did not say when Mbarouk made the
remarks.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanians will display goods and services and establish
further contact with their Congolese counterparts, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sunday Observer, the BET will arrange a
meeting for the business community in Dar es Salaam Monday to
discuss how to benefit most from the visit.
</P>
<P>
The BET chief said the tour to Congo (K) follows findings and
recommendations of a mission which visited Lubumbashi in early
February this year to explore trade prospects there.
</P>
<P>
He said the mission concluded that Tanzania has very good
trade prospects with Congo (K), particularly in the eastern and
southern parts of the central African country where Kiswahili,
Tanzania's national language, is widely spoken.
</P>
<P>
The BET chief said the trade prospect between Tanzania and
Congo (K) is bright with the improvement of transport and
communication links between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania Zambia Railway Authority (TAZARA), Zambia
Railways and Congolese Railways signed an agreement in February
to accelerate the transportation of imported and exported goods
of Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tanzania Central Freight Bureau has signed a
cooperation agreement with the Congo (K)'s Office for Maritime
Freight Management to jointly handle Congolese exports and
imports passing through Dar es Salaam port.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Air Tanzania introduced twice-weekly
flights to Lubumbashi to speed up the movement of passengers and
cargo between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
