<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC to Increase Cooperation in Education, Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The fifth meeting of the SAARC
Technical Committee on Education, Culture and Sports envisaged
several programs to promote cooperation in this regard among
members of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC).
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held on May 26 and 27 in Thimphu, capital of
Bhutan, worked out a calendar of activities for 1999 and also
identified some activities to be funded under the SAARC-Japan
Special Fund, the Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat said in a
press release Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reviewed the progress made in seven priority areas
including education, networking arrangements for sharing
information on mass literacy programs, preparation of an anthology
of short stories of the SAARC region and joint production of
books, audio and visual cassettes, the secretariat noted.
</P>
<P>
It said the meeting submitted a proposal for the implementation
of an SAARC chairs, fellowships and scholarships scheme.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC leaders directed at their second summit in November
1986 that action be taken for an early institution of SAARC
chairs, fellowships and scholarships to promote increasing
cross-fertilization of ideas through greater interaction among
students, scholars and academics in the SAARC countries.
</P>
<P>
The technical committee also decided that Pakistan will prepare
a concept paper to create a consortium of open universities in the
region.
</P>
<P>
So far, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, India and Bangladesh have such
universities in the region and Nepal is in the process of
establishing them.
</P>
<P>
During their ninth summit held in May 1997 in Male, the
Maldives, the SAARC leaders recognized the constraints in
resource, manpower and infrastructure to the promotion of
vocational and higher education in the region.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the possibility of the creation of a
consortium of open universities in the region should be explored,
noting that new and innovative methods like open learning and
distance education can play an effective role in meeting regional
needs in a cost-effective and flexible manner.
</P>
<P>
A tour program by ship for youth of the SAARC countries under
the title SAARC-Ship was also envisaged at the meeting of the
technical committee, the SAARC Secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC, formed in December 1985, has seven member countries
including Bhutan, Bangladesh, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan
and Sri Lanka. Under it are 11 technical committees responsible
for formulating programs and preparing projects in their
respective fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
