<HEADLINE> United States Ties Scotland in Warm-up (Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States showed they
were well tuned-up for the World Cup finals by fighting a goalless
match against Scotland in a warm-up here Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
After calling back all the starters, U.S. coach Steve Sampson
tried a new system that organized the 10 field players into three
defenders, six midfielders and one forward.
</P>
<P>
The formation worked well. Supported by a packed yelling crowd
of nearly 30,000, the Americans dominated the field from the first
whistle, pressing all-out and created several scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
But its seemed that they still need to polish their shooting
skills in front of the goalmouth.
</P>
<P>
Scotland also lost a good chance to score in the 58th minute
when Kevin Gallacher got a clear pass and found nobody in front of
him but the goalkeeper to beat, however, the striker's flat shot
was blocked right by Kasey Keller's left foot.
</P>
<P>
Six minutes later, Scotland's Darren Jackson was given a yellow
card for pushing. Referee Felipe Ramos of Mexico had to control
his temper after being booed again and again by the crowd.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Word Cup group opponents are Germany, Yugoslavia and
Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
