<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Financial Crisis Eased, but Economy Unstable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The Russian financial crisis started
to ease after the Russian Central Bank raised the credit interest
rates sharply twice, but the financial situation remains unstable.
</P>
<P>
As the Russian media reported on Saturday, the panic, that hit
the financial market days ago, started to die away with demand for
the U.S. dollar on the ebb and prices of long-term government
securities and corporate bonds on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The central bank bought 300 million dollars in the off-record
transactions on May 28, seen by experts as a sign of the ending of
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In mid-May, some foreign banks and companies drew loads of
capitals by dumping Russia's short-term government securities and
corporate bonds, which shocked the Russian stock market.
</P>
<P>
The following turmoil, controlled for a while after the central
bank raised the interest rates of credit and short-term
securities, deteriorateed in the past days: the return rate of the
short-term securities rose to 80 percent, the exchange rate
between the dollar and the ruble climed to 1:6.2, exceeding the
1:6.188 exchange corridor, and stock prices dropped an average of
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a desperate effort to calm the financial market and to
prevent the rubble from further depreciation, the Russian
government raised the interest rates of credit again on May 27,
from 60 percent to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Moscow has stepped up tax collection to fill the
state coffers.
</P>
<P>
These efforts won approval from the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), which, in return, awards Moscow with a loan of 670 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Though the Kremlin claims that it has controlled the financial
situation, the media are not as optimistic.
</P>
<P>
On the surface, the Russian crisis seem related to the Asian
financial storms, the slipping world oil prices and the fleeing of
foreign capital, but the real reason, the media believe, lies deep
in its stagnant economy.
</P>
<P>
The sluggish Russian economy, though having stopped sliding,
remains burdened by foreign debts with zero growth, has largely
shattered investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
To readdress the situation, the Russian government once
promised to increase income through enhanced taxes rather than new
borrowings from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Moscow now has in hand 14 billion U.S. dollars of foreign
reserves, not enough to meet its import need for a long time. It
is widely believed that crisis might strike again at any time
unless the Russian economy starts to grow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
