<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nateq-Nouri Re-elected as Iran's Majlis Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative Majlis
(Parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri was re-elected on
Sunday for another one-year term after the rival moderate faction
failed to announce a strong nominee to challenge him.
</P>
<P>
In the internal elections of the 270-seat Majlis, which was
broadcast live by Tehran radio, Nateq-Nouri secured 165 votes from
256 members of the parliament (MP) present and his rival candidate
Majid Ansari only gained 84 votes.
</P>
<P>
It was the seventh term for Nateq-Nouri as Majlis speaker since
he was elected in 1992 during the fourth Majlis elections. He was
re-elected by gaining 211 out of 243 votes last year in spite of
his disgraced failure in the May presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The pro-moderate daily Iran News reported on Sunday that the
MPs from the two rival factions held a session on Saturday and
reached an agreement over the re-election of Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
The two factions also agreed to elect Ansari, head of the
Hezbollah Assembly in the Majlis, as the second vice speaker to
replace the conservative Ali Movahedi Kermani, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
So far the result of the election of vice speakers has not been
announced.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the moderates failed to reach an
agreement on their candidate for the post of Majlis speaker due to
"the lack of harmony" within the faction. Some of the moderates
insisted to take over the speakership while others said that
Nateq-Nouri has changed his manners during the past year following
his defeat in the presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Moderate MP Elyas Hazrati said last week that Nateq-Nouri's
performance in the past year was good, especially toward the
administration of President Mohammad Khatami. Nateq-Nouri
succeeded to direct the Majlis toward cooperation with the
government, he said.
</P>
<P>
Before the Majlis internal elections, Iranian supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei received the MPs on Saturday, calling for
unity between the two rival factions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
