<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Develop New Variety of White Clover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have succeeded
in cultivating a fine variety of white clover, making it possible
to improve grassland in south China, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
A brainchild of animal husbandry departments and the
Agricultural University of Sichuan Province, the new variety of
large-leaved white clover was tested to contain more than 25
percent of crude protein, and to yield 52,500 to 90,000 kilograms
of grass per hectare annually.
</P>
<P>
Research departments have spent 200,000 yuan on the project
since they first imported the grass seed in the 1970s, which, in
turn, have created nearly 8 billion yuan worth of economic
returns.
</P>
<P>
Tests also show that the clover can grow in subtropical zones
at an elevation of 200 to 3,500 meters, and a temperature of 37 to
-13 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
The new variety can also serve as an ornamental plant as well
as a nectar source, and is helpful for water and soil
conservation.
</P>
<P>
South China lacks of natural grassland of the bean family, and
has only 13 percent of quality grassland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
