<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Marks World No Tobacco Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan health authority has
initiated two special programs to mark the World No Tobacco Day
which falls on May 31, health authority sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The aim of these programs is to create awareness among the
public especially the younger generation about how to get rid of
the addiction to smoking and dangerous drugs and alcohol, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that under the programs, the authority has
already conducted several seminars in Colombo, Nuwara Eliya
district, Gall city and Anuradhapura town.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan Cancer Society organized an essay competition
and an oratorical contest among school children in several towns
last week.
</P>
<P>
Current smoking trends continue to rise in the country, with
some smokers consuming more than 50 cigarettes a day, according to
the local press.
</P>
<P>
About 17,000 Sri Lankans die annually due to tobacco-related
illnesses and many thousands more suffer from heart disease and
cancer.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has banned tobacco and alcohol advertisements on
television and radio since the 1980s, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
