<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Soil Conservation Project Planned on Loess Plateau (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China is to undertake its largest
environment protection project on the Loess Plateau to control
soil erosion and desertification.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is expected to be completed in three
decades, will become one of the most important bases for China's
energy and raw material production in the coming century.
</P>
<P>
The short-term objective for the project is to check the
deteriorating ecological environment and to limit the area of soil
erosion and desertification on the plateau in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The next step is to make further improvement on the overall
ecological environment on the plateau by bringing more than 60
percent of soil erosion area under control.
</P>
<P>
Situated on the middle and upper reaches of the Yellow River,
the Loess Plateau is one of the regions with worst soil erosion in
the world.
</P>
<P>
As it cuts through the plateau, the Yellow River will yearly
carry 1.6 billion tons of soil and sand to the lower valley region
of the river.
</P>
<P>
Environment experts said that the annual economic losses from
soil erosion on the plateau amounted to more than 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Soil erosion is a big problem in China as a whole. Statistics
show that the total soil-erosion area in China accounts for 38.2
percent of its total land area, in addition to an annual expansion
of the erosion area of 2,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has attached importance to soil erosion
control on the Loess Plateau. Since 1996, China increased funds to
water and soil conservation projects on the plateau by more than
105 million yuan a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Soil Conservation Project Planned on Loess Plateau (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The water and soil protection project on the plateau also
caught the attention of international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, a water-soil conservation project funded by the World
Bank started on the plateau, which covered 23 counties in Shanxi,
Shaanxi and Gansu provinces and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
The project using a 126-million-U.S.-dollar World Bank loan
aimed to transform arable land on slopes into farmland with stable
crop yields and to raise grain output by planting trees and grass.
</P>
<P>
The project also involved building sand-breaks on nine rivers
to prevent sand from draining into the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
According to a World Bank official who just visited the
project, the World Bank plans to arrang its second batch of loans
for the project.
</P>
<P>
Huang Ziqiang, deputy director of the Yellow River Water
Conservancy Committee, said that water and soil conservation on
the Loess Plateau has been successful.
</P>
<P>
He said that at present, China has completed water-soil
conservation works on an area covering 160,000 square kilometers
on the Loess Plateau, which accounts for 40 percent of the
soil-erosion area of the plateau.
</P>
<P>
The works, which have helped more than 10 million farmers get
sufficient food and drinking water, led to an annual increase of 4
billion kilograms of grain, to more than 8 million cubic meters of
 water in storage and to an annual reduction of 300 million tons
of sand from draining into the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
But some scientists noted that soil erosion is still serious
due to the loose structure of the soil and frequent storms on the
plateau.
</P>
<P>
You Lianyuan, a research fellow of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, said that water and soil conservation works on the
plateau call for efforts of several generations and for more funds
before the ecological problems are thoroughly settled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
