<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good U.S.-China Relations in Interest of Both: Brzezinski </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- A constructive strategic
partnership between the United States and China is of importance
not only to regional stability in Asia but also to global
stability as a whole, says former U.S. national security adviser
Zbigniew Brzezinski.
</P>
<P>
Brzezinski, who is now a senior adviser at the Center for
Strategic and International Studies in Washington, said Chinese
President Jiang Zemin's visit to the U.S. last fall generated a
significant improvement, both in the atmospherics and in the
substance of U.S.-Chinese relations.
</P>
<P>
"There is strong recognition on both sides that good relations
are in the interest of each of the two parties," Brzezinski said
in a recent written interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Frequent and regular American-Chinese dialogue on strategic
issues is necessary so that the two countries are able to consult
one another on matters of general as well as specific interest,"
said Brzezinski, who served as national security adviser to
President Carter.
</P>
<P>
"Both countries share an interest in resolving conflicting
issues, though disagreements and different perspectives on some of
them are inherent both in history and in the different
geopolitical settings in which the two countries respectively
operate, " he said. In addition to discussing these issues in a
constructive fashion, it is desirable to expand the scope of
concrete cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"One very specific step to advance that goal would be to
include China in the annual meeting of the G-7, which has recently
been expanded to G-8, " Brzezinski said, adding, "China is
certainly qualified, in every respect, to be a member of that
group, given its present composition."
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question how to enhance mutual understanding,
Brzezinski said, "Mutual understanding can be best advanced by
more frequent contacts not only between the governments of the two
countries but also between their societies as a whole."
</P>
<P>
To be truly constructive, such contacts must be unhindered by
any form of official impediments and should be as wide-ranging as
possible, he said. In the age of global communications and growing
economic interdependence, any effort to impose a specific
doctrinal perspective is bound to be counterproductive to a good
relationship.
</P>
<P>
Talking about China's role in regional and world affairs,
Brzezinski said China is clearly a source of stability in the Far
East and that greatly enhances the important role that China plays
in the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
"The present financial and economic crisis in some Asian
countries further underlines the stabilizing role of China, and
American-Chinese relations should be designed to further
consolidate that stabilizing role," Brzezinski said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
