<HEADLINE> Auto City Introduces New Building Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Changchun, capital of northeast
China's Jilin Province, has introduced a wide range of measures to
spread the use of new building materials to replace the
traditional clay bricks in an effort to protect farmland.
</P>
<P>
A leading office for reform of building materials, which was
established recently, has been authorized to impose fines on those
organizations that refuse to use new wall-building materials, said
local sources.
</P>
<P>
Organizations are required to pay special fees for the
development of new wall-building materials.
</P>
<P>
While giving tax breaks to firms which use new wall-building
materials, the city bans constructing or extending production
lines of clay bricks. It urges factories with existing brick
production lines to produce new wall-building materials with
industrial wastes and cement.
</P>
<P>
Per capita farmland area of Changchun city is 0.2 hectares, but
the city's farmland has been decreasing at a speed of 66.67
hectares annually from the making of clay bricks. The city
produced more than one billion clay bricks in 1996, said local
sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
