<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millions Suffer From Filariasis in North Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- About 20 million people in
Bangladesh's 12 northern districts have been suffering from
filariasis, a disease caused by mosquito bite, press reports said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The was revealed by Dr. Moazzem Hossain, associate professor of
microbiology at Sir Salimullah Medical College, in his
recently-conducted pilot study.
</P>
<P>
The disease-affected districts include Thakurgaon, Dinajpur,
Rangpur, Nilphamari, Panchagarh, Kurigram, Gaibandha, Jaipurhat,
Naogaon, Chapainawabganj, Rajshahi and Lalmonirhat.
</P>
<P>
This disease, which has widely spread in the tropical and
sub-tropical areas, also carried a social stigma with it, Moazzem
said, adding, "Patients come to see doctors only after the
swelling of any part of the body as people are less aware of the
disease."
</P>
<P>
The disease in early stages which last for three to five years
is manifested as allergic symptoms like occasional fever, cough,
asthma, skin diseases, redness, swelling and urticaria, he stated.
</P>
<P>
When it turns into chronic infection following lymphatic
blockage, there is permanent swelling of the legs and other parts
of the body causing sufferings, permanent disability and reduction
in the working capacity of the population, he said.
</P>
<P>
There has been so far no simple tool to diagnose filariasis at
its early stage in the country except microscopic examination of
blood for microfilaria collected at night which is very cumbersome
and difficult and gives false negative results, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
