<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Exports Increase in First Four Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican exports in the first
four months this year totalled 1.63 billion U.S. dollars, a 19.4
percent increase over the same period last year, the Foreign Trade
Promoter (Procomer) said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Exports of livestock and fish products reached 138.32 million
dollars, a 38.35 percent increase compared with the corresponding
period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector contributed 858.64 million dollars with a
14.87 percent growth, while agricultural exports rose by 20.55
percent to reach 633.55 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mauricio Umana Torres, Procomer financial analyst, said that
products like bananas and coffee, favored by better prices in the
international market, also contributed to the increase.
</P>
<P>
The Procomer estimates that the nation's exports would reach
the target five billion dollars at the end of the year if the
momentum is maintained. 
</P>
