<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Condemns Pakistan's New Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary
Kanezo Muraoka Saturday condemned the latest series of nuclear
tests by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Describing them as "extremely dangerous actions which might
rock the nuclear weapon nonproliferation regime from its very
foundations," the top Japanese government spokesman said that
"Japan absolutely cannot accept (the tests)."
</P>
<P>
Muraoka called upon Pakistan to immediately halt nuclear
weapons testing and development and unconditionally participate in
the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) and the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leaders of Japan's two atom-bomb-hit cities also
issued statements, criticizing Pakistan's testing.
</P>
<P>
Hiroshima Governor Yuzan Fujita said Pakistan's nuclear tests
are a violent affront to the wishes of the people of Hiroshima and
around the globe for a nuclear-free world.
</P>
<P>
Nagasaki Governor Genjiro Kaneko said the tests threaten
efforts to prevent nuclear proliferation.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan announced earlier Saturday that it had carried out two
further nuclear tests in the hills of Baluchistan in western
Pakistan, in reply to five nuclear tests conducted by India on May
11 and 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
