<HEADLINE> Former Polluted City Becomes Tourism Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Benxi city, a heavy industrial base
in northeast China's Liaoning province, has become a tourism site
due to successful pollution control.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that visitors to the city reached 1.5 million
in 1997, who spent over 2.7 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The great change has been attributed to the efforts of the
local government made in improving the local environment in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Li Wenxi, deputy mayor of Benxi city, said that the city has
invested 540 million yuan in the improvement of the local
environment in the past decade. Pollution control projects include
reducing and comprehensively utilizing industrial waste.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the amount of dust per sq km has dropped by
three-fourths compared with the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The city has built a 200-sq km forest belt around urban areas
and has achieved an increase rate of 7-8 percent in terms of urban
green areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy mayor, the city's forest coverage rate
had reached 70 percent by the end of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
