<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Give Wealthy Foreigners Residence Visa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 31 (Xinhua) -- You invest here, and we give you
the residence visa.
</P>
<P>
This is the latest policy of Thailand's Immigration Police,
which aims to lure more foreign money into the cash-strapped
country.
</P>
<P>
As Sunday's Bangkok Post reported, foreigners who invest at
least 10 million baht (250,000 U.S. dollars) for at least three
years will be granted temporary residence visas.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a senior immigration officer as saying the
cabinet has allowed the Immigration Police to grant one-year
residential visas to 5,000 qualified foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to bring in at least 50 billion baht (1.25
billion dollars) of foreign investment if the quota is met.
</P>
<P>
The minimum 10-million-baht investment can be done through
investment in limited companies or public companies: Buying
condominiums or special bonds issued by the Finance Ministry or
the Bank of Thailand, or bonds issued by state enterprises which
are guaranteed by the Finance Ministry, or placing a fixed deposit
with a domestic bank.
</P>
<P>
However, foreigners must follow some restrictions. They must
fix their investment for at least three years after receiving the
temporary residence visas.
</P>
<P>
They must buy the condominiums directly from developers. Both
the condominiums and the bonds must not be sold or transferred to
other parties, nor mortgaged within the three-year period. The
fixed deposits must not be involved in any other legal action, nor
used as guarantees.
</P>
<P>
The Immigration Police also have other plans to attract
foreigners' spending in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Immigration Police will allow elderly foreigners or foreign
pensioners to transform their tourist and transit visas into
one-year residence visas to take any therapeutic courses or tour
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Chinese and their families from Indonesia will be
granted renewable one-year residence visas if they have fixed
deposits of at least 3 million baht (75,000 dollars) per case with
a domestic bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
