<HEADLINE> IMF to Decide on Aid to Indonesia Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- An official of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) said here Saturday that his organization will
make a decision on resuming a rescue package to Indonesia as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
IMF Asia Pacific director Hubert Neiss said at the end of a
four-day fact-finding visit to Indonesia that it was highly
unlikely that the next installment of the rescue package brokered
for Indonesia by the IMF would be further delayed.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian economy is deteriorating rapidly and needs
immediate attention, local leading newspapers quoted the IMF envoy
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Neiss said he has no reason to doubt forecasts that the
battered Indonesian economy could contract 10 percent or more in
1998.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the economic reform program and the latest
political developments in the country were very positive and were
being welcomed not only in Indonesia, but also in the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
The IMF would continue financing Indonesia's efforts to
overcome the worsening crisis by initiating an immediate recovery
process, he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF promised last October to provide Indonesia with 10
billion U.S. dollars of a 43 billion dollar fund which the agency
had brokered to bail out the country's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has so far disbursed 4 billion dollars of the 10
billion dollars promised.
</P>
<P>
The third tranche of 1 billion dollars was initially scheduled
to be handed over to Indonesia on June 4, but it was delayed
because of the political turmoil which led to the resignation of
former President Soeharto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
