<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Exercise Against Terrorist Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The Defense Department of the
United States on Saturday held an exercise at its Pentagon
headquarters against terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
About 500 Defense Department employees and law enforcement
officials joined the 10-hour exercise, in which unidentified
radicals split away from a group of Pentagon tourists, took the
defense secretary's staff hostage, then killed hundreds of people
by knocking over a milk jug full of sarin gas.
</P>
<P>
"The bombings in the World Trade Center and Oklahoma City were
wake-up calls," Pentagon spokesman Glenn Flood said. "To ignore
them would be a dangerous assumption to make."
</P>
<P>
The bombings and the sarin gas at a Tokyo subway in 1995 have
pushed the Clinton administration to make the preparation for such
attacks a new priority.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton has announced a plan to develop and
stockpile vaccines against the lethal anthrax bacteria and the
Defense Department has expanded its vaccination program to all
service men and women from the troops in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon also designated 10 states -- Massachusetts, New
York, Pennsylvania, Georgia, Illinois, Texas, Missouri, Colorado,
California and Washington -- where National Guard units will be
specially trained to respond to weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that local governments around the country have
begun sending fire and police forces through anti-terror training.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon was considered the potential ground zero for
nuclear attacks from the Soviet Union during the Cold War. Now the
Pentagon is visited by 150,000 tourists a year. It was considered
as a prime target for terror attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
