<HEADLINE> Equities on BSE Continue to Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Market optimism about a
pre-budget rally failed to materialize and equities suffered a
sharp setback on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) during the week.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index lost 210.71 points to 3686.39 as
against last weekend's close of 3897.1. The national index also
dropped by 81.11 points to end the week at 1644.14 from the
previous close of 1725.25. The BSE-200 and U.S. dollar indexes
were quoted down at 375.74 and 150.74 compared with last weekend's
closes of 391.2 and 160.5.
</P>
<P>
Depressed by Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha's reported hints
at a tough budget in the light of a mounting fiscal deficit,
falling revenue collections and the shadow of economic sanctions
in the wake of India's five nuclear tests in mid-May, sentiment
remained constantly under pressure. Contributing to the mood were
also other factors like the international rating agency Standard &AMP;
Poor's decision to revise the outlook on India's sovereign rating
from "stable" to "negative."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's decision to put off talks on loans worth 800
million U.S. dollars led to the rupee's continuous downslide, to
the historical low of 41.75/78 rupees per U.S. dollar on Friday.
</P>
