<HEADLINE> Confidence in Bulgaria's Ruling Party Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- A survey conducted by the Gallup
International recently showed that confidence in Bulgaria's ruling
United Democratic Forces (UDF) has dropped by around 20 percent
over the past year.
</P>
<P>
The UDF has lost 20 percent of its electorate in the 18-30 age
group and 15 percent of its supporters in the 41-50 age group.
</P>
<P>
May, which marked the government's first year in office, saw a
10 per cent drop in the approval rating.
</P>
<P>
Since he took office last year, Prime Minister Kostov lost 6
percent of his popularity rating.
</P>
<P>
The support for the opposition Congress of the Bulgarian
Socialist Party (BSP) increased slightly among its own electorate
-- from 67 percent in April to 71 percent in May. More than half
of the BSP supporters are aged 60 and over.
</P>
<P>
President Peter Stoyanov still enjoys the top rating of 72
percent, followed by Sofia Mayor Stefan Sofiyanski of 59 percent.
</P>
