<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Fever Kills 1,000 People in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A dengue fever epidemic hitting
Indonesia during the past four months has killed more than 1,000
people, a public health official said.
</P>
<P>
The death toll was recorded in 11 provinces in Indonesia,
Thomas Suroso, director of animal-vector disease control at the
Health Ministry, said Saturday in Semarang, Central Java,
according to reports reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on dengue fever control, Suroso said the
first known dengue fever cases in Indonesia occurred in 1968 in
Jakarta and Surabaya. Since then the incidence of the disease has
tended to increase in number as well as in area.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 there were 31,789 known cases in 27 provinces and 705
people died, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that every year about 2.5 million people of the world
population living in tropical and subtropical countries run the
risk of contracting the disease.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 tropical and subtropical countries have
experienced dengue fever explosions with more than 500,000 cases a
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dengue fever, an acute tropical disease transmitted by
mosquitoes, leaves its victims with fever, rash and severe pains
in the joints and back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0139 </DOCNO>
