<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin recently exchanged opinions
with his US counterpart Bill Clinton on bilateral relations and
the situation in South Asia through a direct telephone line
according to an arrangement.
</P>
<P>
This is the first direct-telephone talk between the two
presidents since the establishment of the direct telephone line
between the Chinese and the United States governments.
</P>
<P>
-- A Chinese Long March 3B rocket carried a Zhongwei I
satellite into orbit yesterday from the Xichang Launch Center in
southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The launch was the 52nd of a three-state liquid-fuel Long March
series and the tenth successful launch by the Long March series
since October of 1996 and the 3rd of a 3B, which is designed and
manufactured by the Carrier Rocket Technology Academy.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin joined several thousand people
watching the performance of the Cleveland orchestra for its
premiere in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the performance, Jiang met with the orchestra's Chef
Executive Thomas Morris and called the performance a significant
event in Sino-U.S. cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China will increase the pace of opening up its agriculture
sector in an effort to help a rural population of nearly 900
million, a senior agricultural official was quoted by Business
Weekly as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, China will lose no time in
modernizing labor-intensive agriculture by introducing
state-of-the-art technology and fine seeds, and is dedicated to
cooperating with foreign countries that perform well in the
agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
-- China will become the fourth largest outbound travel market
after Germany, Japan and the United States as the number of
Chinese outbound travellers is expected to reach 100 million by
2020, according to the World Tourism Organization.
</P>
<P>
The number of Chinese outbound travellers nearly doubled from
2.8 million in 1992 to 5.3 million last year, the organization
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
