<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Open up Its Agriculture Sector for Further Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China will increased the pace of
opening up its agriculture sector in an effort to help a rural
population of nearly 900 million, a senior agricultural official
said in today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Tang Zheng, director-general of the International Cooperation
Department with the Ministry of Agriculture (MOA) said that more
efforts will be made to modernize labor-intensive agriculture by
introducing state-of-the-art technology and fine seeds.
</P>
<P>
"We are dedicated to cooperating with foreign countries that
perform well in the agriculture sector," Tang said.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to stay abreast of the world's latest agricultural
technology, China will join up with Japan this year to set up a
research and information center on the development of biological
agriculture. The total investment is expected to be 20 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to Tang, the MOA plans to conduct 10 projects this
year, in cooperation with Japan, France, Austria, the Netherlands,
Canada and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that the most successful agricultural cooperation
taking place in the country has involved projects assisted by
international organizations to help China alleviate poverty.
</P>
<P>
These organizations include the World Food Program (WFP), the
International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD), and the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The WFP itself has committed to provide food-for-work aid to 60
projects in China, with a total investment of nearly 800 million
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
An IFAD-aided agricultural project across Hunan and Guizhou
provinces, with a loan of 30 million US dollars, will be initiated
this year.
</P>
<P>
"These supported projects in China have achieved a favorable
record and can be cited as models in terms of the implementation
and the impact on the beneficiaries," Tang said.
</P>
<P>
"All these projects are required to follow the strategy of
sustainable development to achieve success in both grain harvests
and environmental improvement," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, China is also helping other countries to
develop their agricultural programs.
</P>
<P>
According to Tang, China developed 600 hectares of land in
Guinea last year to plant paddy rice. With the efforts of 65
Chinese agricultural experts, the rice yield in the project area
reached 6,000 kilograms per hectare.
</P>
<P>
More cooperative agricultural projects will be launched in six
other African countries this year, Tang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
