<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch, Spaniards Enter World Cup Hockey Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Hosts the Netherlands and Spain
won their respective semi-finals on Saturday to duplicate their
Olympic faceoff at the World Cup Field Hockey Tournament in
Utrecht.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands down Australia 6-2 while Spain blanked Germany
3-0 in the semis.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch defeated the Spaniards to win the 1996 Olympic field
hockey title and Saturday's losing semi-finalists suffered the
same fate in Atlanta as well.
</P>
<P>
Defender Bram Lomans hit a hat-trick in the day to help pace
the Dutch side to its third consecutive finals at the World Cup
tournament since 1990. All three goals were scored off
short-corner penalties in the 39th, 47th and 61st minutes.
</P>
<P>
The hosts were the first on scoreboard when forward Tycho van
Meer found the net with a sixth-minute field shot.
</P>
<P>
But the lead was soon offset as Jay Stacy scored his 12th goal
in the 12-team tourney in the 12th minute. Stephen Davies scored
another in the 55th minute to reduce the Dutch lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
Remco van Wijk and Teun de Nooijer, however, each contributed a
goal in the 60th and 69th minutes to seal the game well away from
the Aussies.
</P>
<P>
Van Wijk's goal was set up by van Meer who while running fast
forward chopped down an air-borne deep forward long pass before
centering the ball to van Wijk for the finishing stroke.
</P>
<P>
In the fifth to eighth place playoffs, England nipped Canada
2-1 while holders Pakistan beat South Korea 3-1.
</P>
<P>
In the ninth to 12th place playoffs, New Zealand beat Malaysia
3-2 and India routed Poland 6-2.
</P>
<P>
In the day's placing games for women, China scored its first
win in the Utrecht cup tourney with a 4-2 over India. With the
win the Chinese placed 11th out of 12 teams.
</P>
<P>
England beat Scotland with two unanswered goals to finish
ninth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
