<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Conduct No Further Nuclear Tests: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Saturday that his country has completed its nuclear
program and there would be no further testing.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Pakistan's second largest city
of Lahore, Sharif said Pakistan is ready to hold talks on all the
outstanding issues with India for ensuring peace and tranquillity
in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that Pakistan conducted another nuclear test
Saturday in the wake of the detonation of five nuclear devices
Thursday, according to the Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Sharif stressed that Pakistan's nuclear tests had become
imperative following India's nuclear explosions earlier this month
which had seriously jeopardized the situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan had waited for the response of the
international community on the Indian tests but was deeply
disappointed by the muted reaction.
</P>
<P>
"This left us with no option but to conduct our own tests in
order to safeguard our national security and restore the balance
of power," he said, adding Pakistan could not afford to endanger
its national security.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indian leadership exacerbated the situation further
by their aggressive statements and threats to use nuclear weapons
and attack Pak-held Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Sharif noted that his government initiated peace talks with
India, however, he was disappointed by India's response to the
initiatives aimed at improving the strained relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that instead of furthering the peace process in South
Asia, the Indian leadership poured cold water on all Pakistan's
attempts to forge a peaceful and friendlier relationship with
India.
</P>
<P>
Declaring that Pakistan could not compromise on her national
security, Sharif said the country was forced to have taken extreme
steps.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said his country has now been provided with "a golden
opportunity to change its destination by shaking off the legacy of
slavery and adopt a route to self-reliance and self-sufficiency."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan cannot depend on anyone for its security and neither
it should do so because of its bitter past experience, Sharif
said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has no aggressive designs against anyone, but at the
same time it must be strong enough to deter evil notions of
others," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Pakistan is ready to sign the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty, he said the country would have to think about it
because of the changed circumstances and come with a new strategy.
</P>
<P>
Sharif also said that having attained the nuclear goal,
Pakistan would now pay attention to other issues for the
development and progress of the country. He expressed his optimism
that Pakistan would also succeed in attaining those goals as well.
</P>
<P>
To a question on India's willingness to sign a peace accord
with Pakistan provided Pakistan gave up its stand on Kashmir, he
said no meaningful talks can be held with India without the
solution of this issue which, he believed, is the root cause of
the conflict between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"India must understand that peace in South Asia lies in the
solution of the Kashmir problem," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the time now has come for the world community to
concentrate on solving the Kashmir issue if they want to see an
end to the nuclear proliferation and eliminate the menace once and
for all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0169 </DOCNO>
