<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Ventures Losing Licenses In Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region revoked the licenses of 2,505 overseas-funded companies in
the past three years to try to tidy up the foreign investment
business.
</P>
<P>
The companies' licenses were revoked for various reasons like
having no fixed place of operation, having no organizational
bodies, or having no funds. Seventy-eight percent were from
Taiwan, Macao, and Hong Kong, a regional administration of
industry and commerce official said.
</P>
<P>
After the clearing up campaign, Guangxi has 3,658
overseas-funded enterprises, 3,035 of them from Taiwan, Hong Kong
and Macao. The legitimate companies have combined registered
capital worth 7.12 billion US dollars, 61 percent of that from
overseas, he said. 
</P>
