<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Calls For Self-reliance Against Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Saturday urged the nation to launch a self-reliance program
to ward off anticipated economic sanctions to be imposed by
western countries on Pakistan for its series of nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of the National Economic Council, Sharif
called upon the provinces and the federal government to launch a
self-reliance program and stop dependence on foreign aid and
loans.
</P>
<P>
The Council was holding the meeting to approve the 1998-1999
Annual Plan at a time when Pakistan conducted six nuclear tests in
48 hours in response to India's series of nuclear tests last week.
</P>
<P>
"We have chosen the path of independence and self-reliance. We
have shown the world that Pakistan is capable of defending its
independence. We were left with no choice but to conduct nuclear
test in larger national interests and to preserve our freedom,"
the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We should adopt the habits of austerity and economy and cut
down our expenditures at all levels," he said while urging the
patriotic people to come forward and rise above self interests and
work hard to achieve the goal of self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
"We are not afraid of sanctions," he said. "These are in fact
blessings in disguise. We can live within our means. This has
given us a direction to adopt the way of self-reliance and to do
away with dependence on foreign loans and aids."
</P>
<P>
He asked the Finance Ministry, Planning Commission and Central
Board of Revenue to submit suggestions to the Cabinet on
self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
Both the provincial and federal governments should make
extensive efforts to boost export and production in agriculture
and industrial fields to increase national income, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1998-1999 Annual Plan, the National Economic Council
has already decided to impose a 50 percent cut on all expenditures
except development and the salary components of government
departments, autonomous bodies and corporations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
