<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Proposes Talks With India, Pakistan on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac has
proposed to India and Pakistan that they talk with the world's
major powers in order to give up nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
In an interview here Friday with the U.S. daily Washington Post
which was also carried by the local media Saturday, Chirac
expressed his opposition to the U.S. decision to impose sanctions
on India and Pakistan for conducting the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"The eight or seven powers with the capability to do something
should meet among themselves first to discuss what we can do to
persuade India and Pakistan to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty and to join the negotiations in the Conference on
Disarmament on the cutoff" of the manufacture of fissionable
material, said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
"Then India and Pakistan could join the talks without fearing
they would be humiliated, as they fear now, and we could all work
together to save the Non-Proliferation Treaty which must be
saved," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Chirac said that he and other European leaders believe that
the economic sanctions against the two already poor countries
would only make them even more miserable.
</P>
<P>
"The main effect of such sanctions in these circumstances is
to make the weak suffer even more," he said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that a future conference make clear to India and
Pakistan that they would get help with significant, peaceful
nuclear power programs if they gave up testing and the processing
of weapons-grade nuclear material, according to the Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that he favored providing security guarantees to
India and Pakistan "in one form or another."
</P>
<P>
French diplomats will discuss the proposal by Chirac with
Indian and Pakistani envoys in Paris next week, said the
Washington Post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
