<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Condemns Pakistan's New Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton Saturday
condemned Pakistan for its two more nuclear tests, saying it can
only serve to increase tensions "in an already volatile region."
</P>
<P>
"The United States condemns today's second round of nuclear
tests by Pakistan," Clinton said in a written statement. "These
tests can only serve to increase tensions in an already volatile
region."
</P>
<P>
"With their recent tests, Pakistan and India are contributing
to a self-defeating cycle of escalation that does not add to the
security of either country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called on India and Pakistan to resume their direct
dialogue, to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and reverse
their arms race without conditions.
</P>
<P>
"Both India and Pakistan need to renounce further nuclear and
missile testing immediately and take decisive steps to reverse
this dangerous arms race," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the State Department issued a statement condemning
Pakistan for carrying out two more nuclear explosions.
</P>
<P>
"We are very disappointed that Pakistan continues to ignore the
calls to exercise restraint that were made by the international
community after its first tests," the State Department said.
</P>
<P>
"This action by Pakistan will further set back our continuing
efforts to defuse tensions and halt the spiraling cycle of
provocative action," it added.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan announced earlier Saturday that it carried out two
further nuclear tests in the hills of Baluchistan in western
Pakistan, bringing the total to seven in three days.
</P>
<P>
The State Department statement called on both India and
Pakistan to stop nuclear tests now and avoid any further
provocations that could raise tensions further.
</P>
<P>
"We again urge both Pakistan and India to cease and desist from
any further nuclear or missile tests or any other provocative
action or rhetoric," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
