<HEADLINE> Rivers Spill Banks in Northeastern Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rains which fell in
the past 24 hours have made rivers in northeastern Romania rise
at an alarming level, some of them having registered the biggest
swell in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
According to Rompres news agency, the level of water has
considerably risen in the rivers of Siret, Prut and Jijia. Land
slides and floods have been reported in Botosani, Iasi and Vaslui
counties. Rivers spilled their banks and swamped about 10,000
arable hectares in these counties, dozens of houses have been
flooded and many residents have been urgently evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Specialists say the Prut, the boundary river with the Republic
of Moldova, rolls in 2,400 cubic meters per second, registering
the biggest swell in the past 30 years. It was reported that some
villages in the Republic of Moldova have also been flooded.
</P>
<P>
According to the meteorological forecasts, the flood will be
stopped in a few days. Nevertheless, special units of the counties
stand ready to fully control the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
