<HEADLINE> French Police Discover Killing Plan by Islamists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- French police said Saturday that they
discovered a plan by Islamic extremists to assassinate the rector
of the Mosque of Paris, Dalil Boubakeur, during a raid against
them this week in several places of France.
</P>
<P>
These extremists are suspected to belong to the Armed Islamic
Group (GIA), an Algerian terrorist group which has a support
network in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Some of the arrested Islamists admitted the existence of a plan
to assassinate Boubakeur, Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted
judicial sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
But Boubakeur said that he himself was not aware that he was
targeted by the GIA, when he accepted an AFP telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
French police arrested 55 people during a simultaneous raid
against the Islamists in several European countries Tuesday, a
security operation apparently aimed at improving security for the
Football World Cup finals to be opened in France in June.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen of them are still being detained in police custody and
could face trial.
</P>
<P>
Boubakeur was blamed by the extremists to be too close with the
Algerian government and for repeatedly condemning the massacres of
civilians by the GIA in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
He has been under police protection since he attended the
celebration of the 50th anniversary of the founding of Israel in
Paris and joined a religious ceremony in a Jewish synagogue one
month ago.
</P>
<P>
The assassination of a Muslim religious leader in Paris, Imam
Abdelbaki Sarhaoui, on July 11, 1995, signaled a wave of terrorist
attacks in France.
</P>
<P>
France held the GIA for the attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
