<HEADLINE> U.N. Inspectors Continue Mission in Iraq Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Monitoring and inspections groups
of the U.N. Special Commission in charge of eliminating Iraq's
banned weapons, known as UNSCOM, continued their mission smoothly
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted an official source at the
National Monitoring Department, the Iraqi peer of UNSCOM, as
saying that 11 monitoring groups made surprise and scheduled
visits to 14 sites on Saturday with full cooperation from the
Iraqi side.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that a biological inspection team which arrived
here a week ago made surprise visits to three health sites in
Baghdad while another group of the same team, on board a
helicopter, made scheduled visits to two health sites in Wasit
Province.
</P>
<P>
Another biological team made surprise visits to
under-monitoring sites, while a chemical team which arrived in
Baghdad on Friday made scheduled visits to one of the
under-monitoring sites, said the source.
</P>
<P>
The inspection team in charge of surveying war heads
destruction sites, which arrived here 10 days ago and would
continue its mission for one month, continued their activity on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Since the signing of the Iraq-U.N. weapons inspection
agreement on February 23, U.N. weapons inspection has been going
on smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Iraq must get the health bill from UNSCOM before sanctions
imposed on it after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait can be
lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
