<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Restraint by India, Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Saturday again called on India and Pakistan to exercise
restraint and reduce tensions between them.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to Pakistan's latest nuclear test Saturday, Annan
said, "This further dangerous and senseless escalation of tension
could lead to a nuclear arms race with incalculable consequences,"
according to his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general called upon Pakistan to make a "parallel
declaration" of a moratorium on future tests as India did, and
urged both countries to accede to the Comprehensive Nuclear Test
Ban Treaty without conditions, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief reiterated his offer to the prime ministers of
India and Pakistan to assist them in initiating a "constructive
dialogue," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's nuclear test Saturday came after the five previous
tests conducted Thursday which it said were aimed at deterring
India's nuclear threat. India conducted a total of five nuclear
tests on May 11 and 13. 
