<HEADLINE> North African Countries Seek to Upgrade Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Several North African countries are
seeking to upgrade the efficiency of the railway networks in the
region, urging Europe's help and private sector's participation.
</P>
<P>
In a final communique issued on Saturday, an international
conference on the region's railway called on the European states
to set up joint commissions with North African countries on
upgrading transport system in the region, particularly the railway
network.
</P>
<P>
The conference, held here on Thursday and Friday, was attended
by experts from the Maghreb states as well as representatives of
relevant institutions such as the International Railway Union and
the Arab Union for Railways.
</P>
<P>
Maghreb, founded in 1989, groups Algeria, Libya, Mauritania,
Morocco and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
The delegates urged the North African countries to launch joint
ventures to develop the railway transport within an all-round and
single strategy on railway linkage.
</P>
<P>
The conference, titled "Railways in North Africa -- Present and
Future Strategy," mainly discussed the regional transport policy
for the next decade, Europe's railway development and its impact
on the North African states, and the prospects of railway
transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
