<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-30 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE, Palestinian Leaders Discuss Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU-DHABI, May 30 (Xinhua) -- United Arab Emirates (UAE) Sheikh
Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan Saturday held talks with visiting
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on the latest developments of the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Zayed said Israel should respect the signed
peace agreements before a just, comprehensive and permanent peace
in the Middle East can be realized.
</P>
<P>
He said the Arab nation is in a decisive stage, which requires
Arab rapprochement through an expanded summit to face up to the
Israeli intransigence and protect the legitimate rights of the
Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Palestinians and Israelis have been
stalled over much-delayed Israeli troop withdrawal from the West
Bank and the expansion of settlement.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting between the two leaders, UAE Minister of
State for Foreign Affairs Sheikh Hamdan Bin Zayed al-Nahyan told
reporters that the UAE president underlined the importance of
holding an emergency expanded Arab summit to discuss the
challenges posed to the peace process and probe ways for restoring
the Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here earlier Saturday to seek support from the
UAE for an Arab summit to save the collapsing peace process.
</P>
<P>
He has sought for several months to convene a summit to adopt a
unified Arab stance towards the Israeli intransigence and hardline
policy.
</P>
<P>
He quickened his pace recently in urging the summit after the
U.S. failed to convince Israel to accept its proposal, which
demands a 13 percent withdrawal from the West Bank. Intensive
consultations are under way among Arab states for a mini or
expanded summit to close Arab ranks.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Jordan, Saudi Arabia, Syria and Qatar have reportedly
agreed to attend the summit proposed to be held early June in
Egyptian capital Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
