<HEADLINE> Iran, Yemen Call for Avoidance of Nuclear Arms Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Yemen have called for
efforts to avoid nuclear arms race in the world following the
nuclear tests of India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi Friday called on all
countries in the Middle East to join the Nuclear Non-Proliferation
Treaty (NPT) to avoid possible nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concern over the Pakistani and Indian nuclear
explosions, Kharrazi said that the blame lied entirely on those
countries which refused to attend talks on nuclear disarmament,
the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came as Pakistan carried out its first round of
nuclear tests Thursday in response to India's nuclear explosions
earlier this month. Pakistan set of two others later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Urging countries to refrain from arms race, Kharrazi said that
Iran, as a member of the NPT, would make efforts to create a
nuclear free zone in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
He also called on other regional countries to join hands with
Iran in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yemen voiced support for reining back the
international nuclear arms race, saying such a race would only
lead to more tensions and struggles worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The country's leading state-run daily "El-Thawrah" said in its
editorial Saturday that Yemen was concerned over the successive
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan recently.
</P>
<P>
Yemen called on India and Pakistan to avoid doing anything that
could exacerbate the tension and destabilize the world peace and
security, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
