<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Backs Lebanon's Stance on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French President Jacques
Chirac said on Saturday that France supports Lebanon's rejection
of Israel's proposal to withdraw from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Lebanese and French officials at a ceremony to
reopen the residence of French envoy to Lebanon, Chirac stressed
that Israel should abide by the United Nations Security Council
Resolution 425 to withdraw troops from south Lebanon
unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided on April 1 to endorse the resolution. But it
said that it would not withdraw from south Lebanon before security
arrangements are negotiated with Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the offer, insisting that the withdrawal
be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Israel is now occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip
in south Lebanon with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
areas from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Chirac expressed welcome to Israel's endorsement of the U.N.
resolution and described it as a "positive step."
</P>
<P>
He said that France is willing to cooperate with other
countries concerned to make contribution to a quiet border between
Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
France, which enjoys a traditional relationship with Lebanon,
is keen on playing an active role in the Middle East peace
process, especially mediating between Lebanon, Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Chirac arrived here on Friday for a two-day visit, the third
since he took office in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
