<HEADLINE> Arafat: U.S. to Publicize Proposal on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat said Saturday that the U.S. has promised to announce
its proposal on Israeli withdrawal from West Bank to bring more
pressure on Israelis.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright made the promise in
a recent telephone call to Arafat, but without saying when the
proposal will be made public, he told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
The proposal demands an additional Israeli withdrawal from 13
percent of the West Bank. It was accepted by Palestinians, but
rejected by Israelis on security reasons. The proposal was not
made public as Washington does not want to press Israelis hard.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. appeared to have lost patience somewhat when its
efforts to reactivate the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have
failed due to Israelis' intransigence.
</P>
<P>
Albright also told Arafat that the U.S., the chief Mideast
peace mediator, will announce who is to blame for the failure of
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March
last year due to the much-delayed Israeli withdrawal and the
expansion of settlement in occupied lands.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has said the Palestinian National Authority has the
right to announce the establishment of an independent Palestinian
state in May next year. But Netanyahu warned him not to do so.
</P>
<P>
Albright did not issue any warning against such a state, only
saying that its establishment should be preceded by a consensus of
parties concerned, Arafat told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here earlier Saturday to seek support from the
United Arab Emirates for an Arab summit to save the collapsing
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Underlining the importance of such an emergency expanded
summit, he told reporters that such a meeting must be held so that
Arab countries can adopt a unified stance at a proposed
international conference on the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The international conference was co-proposed by Egypt and
France earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The emergency summit can also help Arab countries formulate a
single stance against the challenges arising from different areas,
said Arafat, adding contacts and efforts have been made to see
such a meeting sealed.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the summit can be held as soon as
possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
