<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Tunisia have agreed to open their airspace
to each other's civil flights and increase air routes, flights and
accessible airports for each other's airlines free of charge, the
El-Alam El-Youm reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Central Department of Air Transport of the
Egyptian Civil Aviation Authority Mohammed Fahim Rayyan said the
project of "open skies" will be implemented by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
This is the first project of its kind between two Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait Petroleum Corporation said on Saturday
that it has planned to increase the output of crude and oil
derivatives to meet the demand of the world oil markets,
especially in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Al-Ramadan, director of international relations of
the corporation, said the corporation has planned to raise the
production capacity to 3.5 million barrels of oil a day and the
refineries' output capacity to 950,000 bpd by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
But he did not elaborate on the current capacities of the
corporation.
</P>
<P>
He said the corporation is seeking to develop its potentials in
the petrochemical industries and set up joint projects with
international companies.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Several North African countries are seeking to upgrade
the efficiency of the railway networks in the region, calling for
Europe's help and private sector's participation.
</P>
<P>
In a final communique issued on Saturday, an international
conference on the region's railway called on the European states
to set up joint commissions with North African countries on
upgrading transport system in the region, particularly the railway
network.
</P>
<P>
The conference, held here on Thursday and Friday, was attended
by experts from the Maghreb states as well as representatives of
relevant institutions such as the International Railway Union and
the Arab Union for Railways.
</P>
<P>
Maghreb, founded in 1989, groups Algeria, Libya, Mauritania,
Morocco and Tunisia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
