<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan Urged to Sign CTBT Without Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Saturday urged India and Pakistan to sign the Comprehensive
Nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) without conditions.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential statement read by Kenyan Njuguna Moses
Mahugu, the 15-member council also called on Pakistan to issue a
public declaration announcing a moratorium on future tests and
experimentation on delivery systems.
</P>
<P>
Expressing its increased concern at the risk of a nuclear arms
race escalating in South Asia, the council strongly supported
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's statement on his profound dismay at
the latest development.
</P>
<P>
The council convened an urgent meeting Saturday afternoon to
discuss Pakistan's nuclear test Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
The test came after Pakistan's five nuclear tests Thursday.
Islamabad said its actions were aimed at defensing its position in
the face of the Indian nuclear threat. On May 11 and 13, India
conducted a total of five nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Mahugu said the council "is actively considering" a draft
resolution on the matter with a view to its quick adoption.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the time of the next meeting and the substance of
the draft, he said the meeting could be "any time" and the draft
resolution may go beyond the Indian and Pakistani tests.
</P>
<P>
It would rather look at the whole question of stability and
security in South Asia, including non-proliferation and
disarmament, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
