<HEADLINE> Pakistan Ambassador Warns India of Further Escalation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's ambassador to the
United Nations said Saturday that his country would watch what
India would do before taking its responding action.
</P>
<P>
"We will be watching exactly what is done by India, what is the
nature of their aggressive designs against Pakistan," Ambassador
Ahmad Kamal told CNN in an interview.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed his country's peace overtures to India and said
Pakistan currently did not intend to mount nuclear weapons on its
ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
But "if the type of provocations that they have done in the
past, threats of nuclear blackmail, threats of action against
Pakistan in Kashmir, in fact even plans for a preemptive attack
against Pakistan, if any such actions are taken, then it would be
the duty of Pakistan to safeguard its national security by all
possible means," Kamal warned.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Saturday, Pakistan carried out two more nuclear tests
in the hills of Baluchistan in western Pakistan, bringing the
total to seven in three days.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton condemned Pakistan for the further
testing, saying it can only serve to increase tensions "in an
already volatile region."
</P>
<P>
"With their recent tests, Pakistan and India are contributing
to a self-defeating cycle of escalation that does not add to the
security of either country," Clinton said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
He called on India and Pakistan to resume their direct
dialogue, to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and reverse
their arms race without condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
