<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 Kenyan Farmers Ordered to Leave Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has ordered 18
Kenyan farmers to leave the country because of their illegal stay
and undertaking agricultural activities contrary to immigration
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyans have been given two weeks to quit Kimwati Village
in Monduli District in north Tanzania's Arusha Region, according
to a report reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The order was issued Friday by Monduli District Commissioner,
Abdallah Kihato, following complaints from Kimwati villagers on
deteriorating relations between them and the illegally staying
Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
Kihato said that the illegal farmers last year invaded the area
bordering Kenya following severe drought which had
affected the neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
Kimwati villagers had received the Kenyans with expectations
that they would return home after the drought subsided, he said,
adding that the Kenyans, however, had remained to stay in the
area and engaged in large-scale farming of beans and wheat farms
which have created some misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
"We expect good neighborliness in line with the stated
immigration laws," the district commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope our friends from Kenya will understand the situation
and leave the area," Kihato added.
</P>
<P>
He has asked the Kenyans to hand over the farms to the
government immediately after harvesting their last products for
this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
