<DOCNO> XIE19980531.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Instability Creates 100,000 More Refugees in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The instability of the political
and military situation has forced some 100,000 more people to
flee their homes in southern provinces of Huila, Namibe and
Cunene in Angola.
</P>
<P>
These new refugees, mainly children, women and old people,
have sheltered themselves around a few cities in Huila Province,
the Angolan News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an official of the Huila provincial
government as saying that the refugees are leading hard lifes as
the local governments has not enough money to provide them with
such emergency relief as foods, medicine and clothes.
</P>
<P>
The official added that epidemic diseases are likely to erupt
at any time in the areas crowded by refugees.
</P>
<P>
Since the year began, the number of refugees in the
war-ravaged southern African country has been increasing as the
remnants of the opposition National Union for Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) keeps making troubles.
</P>
<P>
The representative of the United Nations humanitarian relief
coordination agency to Angola, Francesco Strippoli, disclosed at
a recent press conference held in Luanda that the number of
refugees except those in south Angola has increased to 70,000,
making the total refugee number in the country up to over one
million.
</P>
<P>
Strippoli said that the demand for emergency aid is "evident
and urgent." Cases in which aid workers and vehicles are
attacked are on increase, making the provision of humanitarian
relief more difficult and halting most of the activities of the
non-governmental organizations in Angola, he added.
</P>
<P>
The unstable situation will delay the transition from
emergency relief to development aid, Strippoli said, adding that
the setback in humanitarian relief in Angola has disappointed the
international community.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that "the Angolan people hold no
responsibility" for this development, and emergency relief work
in the country will continue as long as it is needed.
</P>
<P>
Strippoli said that the U.N. agency will call on the
international community to provide more emergency aid if it is
necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
